================
CODE SNIPPETS
================
### Optimize VideoView Rendering in ScrollViews (Swift)

Source: https://github.com/livekit/client-sdk-swift/blob/main/README.md

Demonstrates an alternative method to UICollectionViewDelegate's `willDisplay`/`didEndDisplaying` for managing VideoView visibility in ScrollViews. It uses a timer to periodically update the `isEnabled` property of VideoViews based on cell visibility, saving CPU resources.

```swift
private var allCells = NSHashTable<ParticipantCell>.weakObjects()
```

```swift
public func collectionView(_ collectionView: UICollectionView, cellForItemAt indexPath: IndexPath) -> UICollectionViewCell {

    let cell = collectionView.dequeueReusableCell(withReuseIdentifier: ParticipantCell.reuseIdentifier, for: indexPath)

    if let cell = cell as? ParticipantCell {
        allCells.add(cell)

    }

    return cell
}
```

```swift
func reComputeVideoViewEnabled() {

    let visibleCells = collectionView.visibleCells.compactMap { $0 as? ParticipantCell }
    let offScreenCells = allCells.allObjects.filter { !visibleCells.contains($0) }

    for cell in visibleCells.filter({ !$0.videoView.isEnabled }) {
        print("enabling cell#\(cell.hashValue)")
        cell.videoView.isEnabled = true
    }

    for cell in offScreenCells.filter({ $0.videoView.isEnabled }) {
        print("disabling cell#\(cell.hashValue)")
        cell.videoView.isEnabled = false
    }
}
```

```swift
self.timer = Timer.scheduledTimer(withTimeInterval: 0.1, repeats: true, block: { [weak self] _ in
    self?.reComputeVideoViewEnabled()
})
```

--------------------------------

### Enable Application Audio Capture in LiveKit Swift

Source: https://github.com/livekit/client-sdk-swift/blob/main/Docs/ios-screen-sharing.md

Configure the LiveKit client to capture application audio during screen sharing by setting `appAudio` to true in `ScreenShareCaptureOptions`. This mixes app audio with the local participant's microphone track.

```swift
let roomOptions = RoomOptions(
    defaultScreenShareCaptureOptions: ScreenShareCaptureOptions(
        appAudio: true // enables capture of app audio
    )
)

// Option 1: Using SwiftUI RoomScope component
RoomScope(url: wsURL, token: token, enableMicrophone: true, roomOptions: roomOptions) {
    // your components here
}

// Option 2: Using Room object directly
try await room.connect(
    url: wsURL,
    token: token,
    roomOptions: roomOptions
)
try await room.localParticipant.setMicrophone(enabled: true)
```

--------------------------------

### Start Screen Share Broadcast Capture

Source: https://github.com/livekit/client-sdk-swift/blob/main/Docs/ios-screen-sharing.md

This Swift code snippet demonstrates how to initiate screen sharing using the Broadcast Capture mode in LiveKit. It calls the setScreenShare method on the local participant with the enabled parameter set to true. Ensure the broadcast extension and app groups are correctly configured beforehand.

```swift
try await room.localParticipant.setScreenShare(enabled: true)
```

--------------------------------

### Publish Camera at 60 FPS (Swift)

Source: https://github.com/livekit/client-sdk-swift/blob/main/README.md

Shows how to publish a camera track with a target frame rate of 60 FPS using the LiveKit Swift client SDK. It involves specifying the FPS during track creation and in the publish options.

```swift
// Create a LocalVideoTrack by calling LocalVideoTrack.createCameraTrack(options: CameraCaptureOptions(fps: 60)).
// Publish with LocalParticipant.publish(videoTrack: track, publishOptions: VideoPublishOptions(encoding: VideoEncoding(maxFps: 60))).
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Broadcast Upload Extension - SampleHandler

Source: https://github.com/livekit/client-sdk-swift/blob/main/Docs/ios-screen-sharing.md

This Swift code configures the SampleHandler for a Broadcast Upload Extension in LiveKit. It overrides the enableLogging property to true, which enables logging for troubleshooting via the macOS Console app. This is specifically for iOS and requires a minimum of macOS Catalyst 13.1.

```swift
import LiveKit

#if os(iOS)
@available(macCatalyst 13.1, *) 
class SampleHandler: LKSampleHandler {
    override var enableLogging: Bool { true }
}
#endif
```

--------------------------------

### iOS LiveKit Room Connection and Video Publishing

Source: https://github.com/livekit/client-sdk-swift/blob/main/README.md

Connect to a LiveKit room using a URL and token, then publish local camera and microphone tracks. This example demonstrates basic room connection and media stream publishing within an iOS application using UIKit.

```swift
import LiveKit
import UIKit

class RoomViewController: UIViewController {

    lazy var room = Room(delegate: self)

    lazy var remoteVideoView: VideoView = {
        let videoView = VideoView()
        view.addSubview(videoView)
        // Additional initialization ...
        return videoView
    }()

    lazy var localVideoView: VideoView = {
        let videoView = VideoView()
        view.addSubview(videoView)
        // Additional initialization ...
        return videoView
    }()

    override func viewDidLoad() {
        super.viewDidLoad()
        view.backgroundColor = .white

        let url = "ws://your_host"
        let token = "your_jwt_token"

        Task {
            do {
                try await room.connect(url: url, token: token)
                // Connection successful...

                // Publishing camera & mic...
                try await room.localParticipant.setCamera(enabled: true)
                try await room.localParticipant.setMicrophone(enabled: true)
            } catch {
                // Failed to connect
            }
        }
    }
}

extension RoomViewController: RoomDelegate {

    func room(_: Room, participant _: LocalParticipant, didPublishTrack publication: LocalTrackPublication) {
        guard let track = publication.track as? VideoTrack else { return }
        DispatchQueue.main.async {
            self.localVideoView.track = track
        }
    }

    func room(_: Room, participant _: RemoteParticipant, didSubscribeTrack publication: RemoteTrackPublication) {
        guard let track = publication.track as? VideoTrack else { return }
        DispatchQueue.main.async {
            self.remoteVideoView.track = track
        }
    }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Manual Track Publication with BroadcastManager in LiveKit Swift

Source: https://github.com/livekit/client-sdk-swift/blob/main/Docs/ios-screen-sharing.md

Manually manage screen share track publication by disabling the default behavior and using `BroadcastManager` with either a Combine publisher or a delegate to detect broadcast state changes.

```swift
BroadcastManager.shared.shouldPublishTrack = false
```

```swift
let subscription = BroadcastManager.shared
    .isBroadcastingPublisher
    .sink { isBroadcasting in
        // Manually handle track publication
    }
```

```swift
class MyDelegate: BroadcastManagerDelegate {
    func broadcastManager(didChangeState isBroadcasting: Bool) {
        // Manually handle track publication
    }
}
BroadcastManager.shared.delegate = MyDelegate()
```

--------------------------------

### Disable Automatic AVAudioSession Configuration in Swift

Source: https://github.com/livekit/client-sdk-swift/blob/main/Docs/audio.md

Disables the LiveKit SDK's automatic configuration of AVAudioSession, which is useful when other frameworks like CallKit manage the session.

```swift
AudioManager.shared.audioSession.isAutomaticConfigurationEnabled = false
```

--------------------------------

### Bypass Voice Processing at Run-time in Swift

Source: https://github.com/livekit/client-sdk-swift/blob/main/Docs/audio.md

Allows bypassing voice processing features at run-time by calling the AVAudioEngine's isVoiceProcessingBypassed method. This provides a smoother experience for dynamic changes.

```swift
AudioManager.shared.isVoiceProcessingBypassed = false
```

--------------------------------

### Disable Voice Processing in Swift

Source: https://github.com/livekit/client-sdk-swift/blob/main/Docs/audio.md

Disables Apple's voice processing features (echo cancellation, auto-gain control) by re-creating the internal AVAudioEngine. Recommended to set before connecting to a room.

```swift
AudioManager.shared.isVoiceProcessingEnabled = false
```

--------------------------------

### Integrating LiveKit with CallKit for Background Calls

Source: https://github.com/livekit/client-sdk-swift/blob/main/README.md

This snippet demonstrates how to integrate LiveKit with Apple's CallKit framework to handle background-triggered incoming calls. It involves synchronizing LiveKit's audio session with CallKit's by activating and deactivating the shared audio session instance and disabling automatic audio session configuration within the AudioManager.

```swift
import LiveKitWebRTC

func provider(_ provider: CXProvider, didActivate audioSession: AVAudioSession){
    LKRTCAudioSession.sharedInstance().audioSessionDidActivate(audioSession)
    // ...
}
func provider(_ provider: CXProvider, didDeactivate audioSession: AVAudioSession) {
    LKRTCAudioSession.sharedInstance().audioSessionDidDeactivate(audioSession)
    // ...
}
```

```swift
AudioManager.shared.audioSession.isAutomaticConfigurationEnabled = false
```

--------------------------------

### Install LiveKit with CocoaPods

Source: https://github.com/livekit/client-sdk-swift/blob/main/Docs/cocoapods.md

Add the LiveKit podspec source and the LiveKit client pod to your Podfile to install the SDK. This method is for iOS and macOS platforms.

```ruby
source "https://cdn.cocoapods.org/"
source "https://github.com/livekit/podspecs.git" # <-

platform :ios, "18.0"

target "YourApp" do
    pod "LiveKitClient", "~> 2.2.0"

